## Path A — AWS EC2 Image Builder (Recommended)

Image Builder runs your component inside a managed pipeline and handles AMI hardening, tagging, and distribution. The two artifacts (`component.yaml` + `image-builder-recipe.json`) compose into one pipeline.
{{- if eq .Install "native" }}

### Prerequisites (native install only)

The `component.yaml` installs Horde by syncing binaries from S3. Before proceeding:

1. Publish the Horde server binaries from your UE source checkout:
   ```bash
   cd Engine/Source/Programs/Horde
   dotnet publish HordeServer/HordeServer.csproj -c Release -o /tmp/horde-bin
   ```
2. Upload them to an S3 bucket your Image Builder instance profile can read:
   ```bash
   aws s3 sync /tmp/horde-bin/ s3://YOUR_BUCKET/horde-bin/
   ```
3. Open `component.yaml` and replace `REPLACE_WITH_YOUR_BUCKET` with your actual bucket name.
{{- end }}

### 1. Create the custom component

```bash
aws imagebuilder create-component \
  --region {{ .Region }} \
  --name {{ .Name }}-{{ .Install }} \
  --semantic-version 1.0.0 \
  --platform Linux \
  --supported-os-versions "Ubuntu 22" \
  --data file://component.yaml
```

The command prints the new component's ARN — copy it. It looks like:

```
arn:aws:imagebuilder:{{ .Region }}:123456789012:component/{{ .Name }}-{{ .Install }}/1.0.0/1
```

### 2. Substitute the ARN into the recipe

`image-builder-recipe.json` contains a placeholder string `REPLACE_WITH_CUSTOM_COMPONENT_ARN`. Replace it with the ARN from step 1.

### 3. Create the recipe

```bash
aws imagebuilder create-image-recipe \
  --region {{ .Region }} \
  --cli-input-json file://image-builder-recipe.json
```

### 4. Create an infrastructure configuration and image pipeline

Use the AWS console (Image Builder → Image pipelines → Create) or `aws imagebuilder create-infrastructure-configuration` / `create-image-pipeline`. This part is one-time setup per AWS account.

### 5. Run the pipeline

```bash
aws imagebuilder start-image-pipeline-execution \
  --region {{ .Region }} \
  --image-pipeline-arn <pipeline-arn>
```

When the pipeline finishes, note the new AMI ID and update `fabrica.yaml`:

```yaml
horde:
  amiId: ami-<id>
```

