## Path B — Packer (alternative)

Packer drives a builder EC2 instance directly without the Image Builder service.

### 1. Initialize and validate

```bash
packer init packer.pkr.hcl
packer fmt -check packer.pkr.hcl
packer validate packer.pkr.hcl
```

### 2. Build the AMI

{{ if eq .Install "native" -}}
You must publish the Horde binaries first from your UE source checkout:

```bash
cd Engine/Source/Programs/Horde
dotnet publish HordeServer/HordeServer.csproj -c Release -o /tmp/horde-bin
```

Then run Packer with the path to those binaries:

```bash
packer build -var "horde_source_dir=/tmp/horde-bin" packer.pkr.hcl
```
{{- else -}}
> **Before running Packer:** `/opt/horde/docker-compose.yml` is **not** baked into this AMI.
> The `horde` systemd unit runs `docker compose up -d` from `/opt/horde/`, so this file must
> exist before the instance boots. Add a `file` provisioner (or a heredoc in the shell provisioner)
> to write your `docker-compose.yml` — use the official copy from
> `Engine/Source/Programs/Horde/HordeServer/docker-compose.yml` in your UE source checkout.
> See the `TODO` comment at the top of `packer.pkr.hcl` for the exact provisioner pattern.

```bash
packer build packer.pkr.hcl
```
{{- end }}

Packer prints the new AMI ID at the end. Update `fabrica.yaml`:

```yaml
horde:
  amiId: ami-<id>
```

{{ end -}}
